{"data":{"logo":{"childImageSharp":{"fixed":{"base64":"data:image/png;base64,","width":400,"height":128,"src":"/angusmorton.com/static/2b5eaa0de166a8b5faebad4955c2200c/51380/ghost-logo.png","srcSet":"/angusmorton.com/static/2b5eaa0de166a8b5faebad4955c2200c/51380/ghost-logo.png 1x"}}},"markdownRemark":{"html":"<p>Android has a relatively unpredictable habit of killing any <code class=\"language-text\">Activity</code> that is not immediately visible to the user to reclaim memory. Because of this we need a way to test how our app behaves when our Activities are killed. ‘Don’t keep activities’ forces Android to kill background activities (as though it were in a low memory environment).\nFrom the <a href=\"http://developer.android.com/tools/debugging/debugging-devtools.html\">Android Developer Documentation</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Tells the system to destroy an activity as soon as it is stopped (as if Android had to reclaim memory) This is very useful for testing the <code class=\"language-text\">onSaveInstanceState(Bundle)</code> / <code class=\"language-text\">onCreate(android.os.Bundle)</code> code path, which would otherwise be difficult to force. Choosing this option will probably reveal a number of problems in your application due to not saving state. For more information about saving an activity’s state, see the Activities document.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Don’t keep activities is in the <strong>Developer options</strong> settings of your device.</p>\n<p><em>Consider enabling this to test that your app saves state properly.</em></p>","htmlAst":{"type":"root","children":[{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Android has a relatively unpredictable habit of killing any "},{"type":"element","tagName":"code","properties":{"className":["language-text"]},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Activity"}]},{"type":"text","value":" that is not immediately visible to the user to reclaim memory. Because of this we need a way to test how our app behaves when our Activities are killed. ‘Don’t keep activities’ forces Android to kill background activities (as though it were in a low memory environment).\nFrom the "},{"type":"element","tagName":"a","properties":{"href":"http://developer.android.com/tools/debugging/debugging-devtools.html"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Android Developer Documentation"}]},{"type":"text","value":":"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"blockquote","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Tells the system to destroy an activity as soon as it is stopped (as if Android had to reclaim memory) This is very useful for testing the "},{"type":"element","tagName":"code","properties":{"className":["language-text"]},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"onSaveInstanceState(Bundle)"}]},{"type":"text","value":" / "},{"type":"element","tagName":"code","properties":{"className":["language-text"]},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"onCreate(android.os.Bundle)"}]},{"type":"text","value":" code path, which would otherwise be difficult to force. Choosing this option will probably reveal a number of problems in your application due to not saving state. For more information about saving an activity’s state, see the Activities document."}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Don’t keep activities is in the "},{"type":"element","tagName":"strong","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Developer options"}]},{"type":"text","value":" settings of your device."}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"element","tagName":"em","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Consider enabling this to test that your app saves state properly."}]}]}],"data":{"quirksMode":false}},"excerpt":